The paper deals with the joint transfer of energy and information in communication networks, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several CS sub-fields. The use of energy harvesting and the analysis of achievable rates suggest that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The consideration of interactive communication between nodes and the derivation of inner and outer bounds on achievable rates suggest that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of numerical simulations to demonstrate the effectiveness of proposed strategies suggests that the paper may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the fact that the paper draws on known results in physics suggests that it may also belong to the Physics (cs.PHYS) sub-category.
